91 Existing law establishes three tiers of affordable housing for various purposes in existing
92 law and defines “affordable housing” as housing that falls within any of the three tiers. (NRS
93 232.860, 244.189, 244.287, 268.058, 268.190, 278.0105, 279.385, 279A.020, 279B.020,
94 315.9625, 319.042) Section 33 of this bill revises the term “affordable housing” to be
95 “attainable housing.”
96 Under existing law, the tiers are based on both household income and the costs of housing
97 as a percentage of that income. With respect to household income: (1) “tier one affordable
98 housing” is housing for a household which has a total monthly gross income that is equal to
99 not more than 60 percent of the median monthly gross household income for the county in
100 which the housing is located, which is commonly known as the area median household
101 income; (2) “tier two affordable housing” is housing for a household which has a total
102 monthly gross income that is equal to more than 60 percent but not more than 80 percent of
103 the area median household income; and (3) “tier three affordable housing” is housing for a
104 household which has a total monthly gross income that is equal to more than 80 percent but
105 not more than 120 percent of the area median household income. In addition, with respect to
106 the costs of housing, affordable housing under existing law is housing that costs not more than
107 30 percent of the total monthly gross household income of the household with an income at
108 the maximum percentage of the area median household income for the tier. (NRS 278.01902,
109 278.01904, 278,01906) Section 29 of this bill creates a new tier of affordable housing, to be
110 known as “tier four affordable housing,” that addresses housing for a household that has a
111 total monthly gross income that is equal to not more than 120 percent but not more than 150
112 percent of the area median household income.
